4572864</reference></references><venue id="1153524033" type="C">International Cryptology Conference</venue><doi>10.1007/978-3-642-01001-9_27</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.64825">Pseudorandom function family</keyword><keyword weight="0.41125">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.63435">Pseudorandomness</keyword><keyword weight="0.51372">Block cipher mode of operation</keyword><keyword weight="0.42346">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.57519">Stream cipher</keyword><keyword weight="0.62129">Pseudorandom permutation</keyword><keyword weight="0.63749">Pseudorandom generator theorem</keyword><keyword weight="0.5056">Bounded function</keyword><keyword weight="0.56447">Pseudorandom number generator</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>A weak pseudorandom function (wPRF) is a cryptographic primitive similar to --- but weaker than --- a pseudorandom function: for wPRFs one only requires that the output is pseudorandom when queried on random inputs. We show that unlike "normal" PRFs, wPRFs are seed-incompressible, in the sense that the output of a wPRF is pseudorandom even if a bounded amount of information about the key is :[65],"an application of this result we construct a simple mode of operation which --- when instantiated with any wPRF --- gives a leakage-resilient stream-cipher. The implementation of such a cipher is secure against every side-channel attack, as long as the amount of information leaked per round is bounded, but overall can be arbitrary large. The construction is simpler than the previous one (Dziembowski-Pietrzak FOCSu002708) as it only uses a single primitive (a wPRF) in a straight forward manner.</abstract></paper>